Task 1 - Bike Journey Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Key Points to Note:¶

Bike journey data¶

This data set contains anonymised bike trip data from the Los Angeles Metro Bike Share, available here: https://bikeshare.metro.net/about/data/. Use the metro.csv data file provided in the CSGitLab Repository. Each row corresponds to a single bike journey. The columns in the data are:

  • trip_id: Locally unique integer that identifies the trip duration Length of trip in minutes.
  • start_time: The date/time when the trip began, presented in ISO 8601 format in local time 1.
  • end_time: The date/time when the trip ended, presented in ISO 8601 format in local time.
  • start_station: The station ID where the trip originated.
  • start_lat: The latitude of the station where the trip originated.
  • start_lon: The longitude of the station where the trip originated.
  • end_station: The station ID where the trip terminated.
  • end_lat: The latitude of the station where the trip terminated.
  • end_lon: The longitude of the station where the trip terminated.
  • bike_id: Locally unique integer that identifies the bike.
  • plan_duration: The number of days that the plan the passholder is using entitles them to ride.
  • trip_route_category: "Round Trip" for trips starting and ending at the same station or "One Way" for all other trips.
  • passholder_type: The name of the passholders plan.
  • bike_type: The kind of bike used on the trip, including standard pedalpowered bikes, electric assist bikes, or smart bikes.

Find a sensible way to remove the missing values from the data frame and explain why you have chosen this method.¶

Two methods of counteracting the missing values in the data set, are by either dropping any records (rows) that have missing values, or by filling them with an arbitrary value - 0 is the value usually chosen however this will significantly effect all of the statistical calculations done on the data. A way of improving this could be to fill with the mean value for that column instead, however this will still affect the statistics, for example if a group of data (in this case something like bike_type) had a significantly lower mean than another subgroup filling missing values with the overall mean would skew the distribution of the subgroups, meaning any cross comparison would be heavily affected.

For this reason - The best course of action was to determine where the missing data lies and what how these the processes would affect the overall results.

The method used to check this, was first performing a count on the amount of cells records which contained data for each field, and also to count which fields were affected by the missing data, how much of the data was missing for each field and what effect that could have overall on the statistics.

The ".count()" function was used to show how many records held data for each field. ('Metro' is the name of the dataframe used). This also gives a good estimate at the total amount of records in the dataset (relying on data not missing in every column). In an ideal situation with no missing data, all of the following values should be the same.

As you can see from the scatter plot; all of the different passholder types show a strong concentration of usage for a short duration, which is to be expected as the amount of people taking trips over 200 minutes (3hr20) will decrease exponentially as most people would not have this time to spare. However, it is clear that the flex pass holders are only purchased for very short trips, and are the least purchased ticket. Testing passes are also predominantly chosen for shorter trips, (possibly being the most popular for extrememly short trips) with an outlier showing a mid-length trip. The one day pass is the most popular choice and clearly displays that a strong proportion of it's users opting for short to mid-range trips, however a large amount of people with the one day pass still taking longer duration trips.

The annual pass shows a diverse spread of duration trips, although the annual pass shows a higher concentration around the 0-200 range and a lower focus around the 200-400 range than the other passes, it still has users who take trips of all durations from extremely quick (0-20) all the way up extremely long (1400+) with a few at various intervals inbetween. The walk up pass is by far the most popular choice for the people who prefer to take longer trips, and the second most popular overall, the distribution of duration for the walkup pass is much more evenly distributed when compared to the one day pass, which has a intense concentration around shorter trips; the walk up trip has a consistent volume of people taking trips of all lengths, and clearly dominates the other pass options for any trips above 600 in duration.

Finally the monthly pass is again a diversely spread distribution of duration tapering out slightly towards the longer length trips but remaining fairly consistent through the mid-length trips (up to 1000). When the overall number of trips by pass holders is considered, it can be deduced that the spread of the monthly pass is greater than any of the other passes as they make up a small proportion of the overall trips by the passholders, but showing a strong appearance throughout all of the time ranges. This would suggest there is no major correlation between usage of the pass and choosing that pass.

To further validate these claims, more variations of representations of data were used, a box and whisker diagram was used to show the interquartile range, the suspected outliers and the median. The whiskers stop at the relative quartile the 1.5 x the interquartile range. This is extremely useful for seeing where the majority of the data lies. As expected, the majority of all the data is in the shortest duration segment. However the graphical representation of the medians becomes extremely useful when comparing the spread of data.

By using a Box & Whisker diagram and zooming in to the most active range, a large amount of information can be inferred. This figure clearly demonstrates the spread of the data. The diagram accurately represents the median, interquartile range (upper quartile - lower quartile) and the "outlying" data. The 'whiskers' show where the data lies within 1.5 times the interquartile range - of the interquartile range. For example, where IQR = Q3 - Q1, the upper 'whisker' will terminate at Q3 + 1.5IQR while the lower 'whisker' will terminate at Q1 - 1.5IQR OR 0 as this data cannot be negative.

The diagrams allow easy visual comparisons of medians, Upper quartile values, Lower quartile values and general spread and density/dispersement of data.

From this, many of the previous hypothesis have been confirmed, showing that while 0 - 150 is by far the most popular duration of the trip, encompassing the core majority of data (from Q1 - IQR >-to-> Q3 + IQR ) for every type of pass. It is apparent that those opting for longer trips tended towards the one day pass, or possibly the walk-up pass, while those opting for the annual or monthly pass stuck to shorter journeys on average.

Next a strip plot was used, this functions similarly to a scatterplot while also making the data much easier to interpret and showing the density much clearer. Overall this is probably the most useful plot for representing this data in a useful and significant manner. It accurately shows the density and concentration of each passholder type and allows easy interpretation of the spread of the data,

Task 2 - Data Clustering - Seed Shape Data¶

research and implementation:¶

Context for the dataset¶

Data sourced from: UCI machine learning repository, originally by M. Charytanowicz, J. Niewczas, P. Kulczycki, P.A. Kowalski, S. Lukasik, S. Zak in A Complete Gradient Clustering Algorithm for Features Analysis of X-ray Images, in: Information Technologies in Biomedicine, Ewa Pietka, Jacek Kawa (eds.), Springer-Verlag, Berlin-Heidelberg, 2010, pp. 15-24. 2

Available here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/seeds#. Use the seeds.csv data file provided in the CSGitLab Repository.

This data set contains measurements of seeds from a number of different plant species. Each row corresponds to a single seed. The columns are:

  • area: The area of the seed.
  • Perimeter: The length of the perimeter of the seed.
  • Compactness: A measure of the area of the seed relative to the perimeter.
  • Length: The length of the seed.
  • Width: The width of the seed.
  • Asymmetry: A measure of the asymmetry of the seed.

  • groove length: The length of the groove in the seed.

    Note: In the dataset provided, the column containing the correct classification of the kernel has been omitted, when compared to the source dataset.

Investigating the optimal number of clusters¶

One downfall of the K-Means method of clustering, is that the number of clusters must be assigned before the algorithm is used, and therefore the number of clusters must also be known.
There are two main methods for evaluating the best number of clusters to sort the data into. The first and most commonly used is: "The Elbow Method". The alternative is "The Silhouette Score method".

The Elbow Method¶

The Elbow Method is a heuristic algorithm, and the most common method used for determining the number of clusters in a dataset. The method produces a plot which usually allows for easy visual interpretation of where the optimal number of clusters would be. The plot should produce a curve, and the "elbow" of the curve acts as the cutoff for the optimal solution. This is usually where the gradient of the curve has a dramatic change before decreasing significantly.
There is not always a clear elbow, if this is the case, further analysis can be performed.

In [30]:
#List to store the metric value given different K values.
inertia = []
#Range of the different values of K to analyse
K = range(2,10)
for k in K:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    km = km.fit(seedSet)
    inertia.append(km.inertia_)

This code performs the training on the dataset for all instances of K, where K is the number of clusters, between 2 and 10. It then records the inertia to a list. From here the data can be plotted, and analysed visually.

In [31]:
plt.plot(K, inertia)
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.show()

A clear 'elbow' can be seen at K = 3, however K = 4 also demonstrates that it may yield an effective solution. Although the solution of K = 3 seems like a suitable choice and is most likely the optimal solution, an argument could be made for K = 4 and confirming the correct number of clusters at this stage is critical to the process. For this reason, further analysis was completed, in the form of a Silhouette score analysis.

The Silhoutte Method¶

The Silhouette method uses Silhouette Score analysis to produce a plot which again can be interpretted visually, on it's own, it is much harder to interpret than a plot derived using the elbow method, however when combined with the elbow plot, it allows a much larger insight into the estimate of the optimal number of clusters.

The Silhouette method calculates a score for each iteration of the process and each value of K (again where K is the number of clusters).
These values lie between -1 and 1. Where:
1 : instance is well inside own cluster, far from other clusters - meaning correct assignment.
0 : near boundary of cluster
-1 : instance is outside cluster therefore assigned to wrong cluster

The silhouette score is the mean silhouette of all of the instances.
The Silhouette Coefficient is (b-a)/ max(a,b)
Where: a = The mean distance to other instances in the same cluster. (Mean Intracluster Distance) b = The mean "Nearest Cluster" distance. The mean distance to all instances of the next nearest cluster, which is defined by the cluster which minimises the value of b.

In [32]:
#import 
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
#list to score metric from different k values. 
s_score = []
#range to anlayse
K  = range(2,10)
for k in K: 
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    kmeans.fit(seedSet)
    s_score.append(silhouette_score(seedSet, kmeans.labels_))

This code first imports the necessary functions from the sklearn metrics library. A list is then created in which the Silhouette scores will be stored. Then the Silhouette score is calculated for each instance of K from 2 to 10. This is then plotted.

N.B. The Silhouette Score Analysis graph will change slightly each time it is calculated due to the randomised starting value. However the Trend should stay approximately the same.

In [33]:
#plotting
plt.plot(K, s_score)
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Silhoutte score')
plt.title('Silhoutte Score analysis')
plt.show()

As shown in the graph, there is a significant drop in Silhouette score between K = 3 and K = 4. This would suggest that the previous hypothesis of K = 3 is correct for the optimal number of clusters for this seed dataset.

Discussion of cluster number¶

As shown above the "Elbow Method" produced a plot which strongly suggested the optimal number of clusters would be 3, however, from this graph alone, it could be proposed that 4 clusters could produce an efficient solution also. For this reason "Silhouette Score Analysis (SSA)" was performed on the same dataset. From this SSA, it was clearly visible that any more than three clusters resulted in a significant decrease in effectiveness, from these two processes together we can clearly confirm that 3 clusters yields the optimal solution.

from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

def plot_kmeans(kmeans, x, n_clusters = 3, rseed=0, ax = None):
    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(x)
    
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    ax.axis('equal')
    ax.scatter(x[:,0],x[:,1], c = labels, s =10, cmap = 'viridis', zorder = 2)
    
    # plot the representation of the kmeans model
    centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_ 
    radii = [cdist(x[labels == i], [center]).max()
            for i, center in enumerate(centers)]
    for c, r, in zip(centers, radii):
        ax.add_patch(plt.Circle(c,r,fc = '#CCCCCC', lw = 3, alpha=0.5, zorder = 1))
    plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='black', s=200, alpha=1);        
    plt.xlabel('Area')
    plt.ylabel('Perimeter')
    plt.title('Area Vs Perimeter')

In [56]:
#plt.bar(nx.betweenness_centrality(g))
#plt.ylabel("Frequency")
#plt.xlabel("Betweenness_Centrality")

Betweenness Centrality is a measure of importance of a node in the network, in terms of possible paths through the network. It is calculated at the fraction of all shortest paths that would pass through that node. Nodes with a high BC often connect separate regions of the network, and are therefore of high importance to the functionality of the network. As these are fractions, they all lie between 0 and 1.
From this we can infer that node 603 is the most interconnected (and subsequently likely most important) in the network.

The assortativity of a network is a measure for how strong the tendency for nodes to interact with other similar nodes is. The assortativity coefficient measures the correrelation of node degrees of interacting edges. Pos = high-high neg = high- low.

In [57]:
nx.degree_assortativity_coefficient(g)
Out[57]:
-0.6682140067239861

This would imply that the network is majority made up of central ndes which act as a hub branching out to less connected nodes.

In [58]:
G = g
layout = nx.spring_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=150,alpha=0.5)

The previous statement is further supported by this graph.

In [59]:
ddist = nx.degree_histogram(G)[1:] # Skip 0 degree nodes
plt.loglog(range(1,len(ddist)+1),ddist,'o')
plt.xlabel("Degree")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
Out[59]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Frequency')

This shows there is an extremely large amount of nodes with a low degree, and a small amount of nodes with an extremely high degree. This further supports the assortivity statement.

Now a Trial and error approach was taken in order to investigate the best layout for displaying the network. These have been rearranged into oder if usefulness.

In [60]:
layout = nx.kamada_kawai_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=5,alpha=0.5)

This is the "Kamada Kawai" representation, a force directed representation, calculated using Kamada-Kawai path-length cost-function.This is a useful representation of the data. It shows the Network as many strongly connected nodes acting as hubs for the less connected nodes, as suspected by the assortivity coefficient.

In [61]:
layout = nx.fruchterman_reingold_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=5,alpha=0.5)

This graph represents the fruchterman-reingold layout of the network, this is possibly the most useful representation, this is another force-directed graph. by lowering the size of the node displayed, a much more visually interpretive view is available.

In [62]:
layout = nx.spring_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=5,alpha=0.5)

The Spring layout is possibly one of the most common and effective ways to displaying graphs, it displays it in a logical and easy to interpret format, again a force-directed layout.

In [63]:
layout = nx.random_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=5,alpha=0.5)

This is a random representation, this is of little-to-no use, however it does show the sheer volume of interconnectivity.

In [64]:
layout = nx.spiral_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=5,alpha=0.5)

This is the spiral layout, while it effectievly demonstrates the volume of interconnectivity and looks extremely aesthetically appealing, it is hard to infer much useful information about the network.

In [65]:
layout = nx.spectral_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=100,alpha=0.5)

The spectral layout offers a small insight into the network, with a smaller network,the complexity and visual representation would be much more effective than with the current system. While this does give some information about the system it is not the most effective representation.

In [66]:
layout = nx.circular_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=150,alpha=0.5)

This is the representation of the network in a circular layout, because of the sheer volume of edges (and nodes), this is not very clear or effective for displaying the relationships of the netwrok, other than showing the small section where there are few connections, this could be a useful view if it was scaled to be a larger image, however the size needed for this amount of data is unrealistic.

In [67]:
layout = nx.shell_layout(G)
nx.draw(G,pos=layout,node_size=20,alpha=0.5)

This is a shell representation, similar to circular representation, if this was scaled to a size that it became interprettable this could be extrememly useful, but that size is not realistically applicable, so this is also not an effective representation due to the sheer volume of data.

NetworkX also includes more layouts, including bipartite, this was not deemed as suitable for this style of network. Planar layout was also not applicable as the data is not planar. Same with multivariate.
